post_text: Many of us recall exactly where we were, what we were doing, and whom we were with during the events that unfolded on September 11, 2001. As educators and parents, we are now teaching those same events as history to our children. Today we take time to mark the nineteenth anniversary of the attacks on America and pay tribute to our first responders, military personnel, and families who suffered loss because of that tragic day.

REMINDER: Through the USDA and the CoronaVirus Food Assistance Program, a USDA mixed box of wholesome Prairie Farms dairy products consisting of (2) one-gallon jugs of 2% milk, (2) 14-ounce containers of premium chocolate milk, (2) 14-ounce containers strawberry milk, (1) 16-ounce container of french onion dip, (1) 16-ounce container of sour cream, (1) 8-ounce block of cream cheese or (1) block of baby swiss cheese, and (1) 24-ounce container of small curd cottage cheese. There will be 1,056 boxes of dairy products.

Also, there will be a trailer load of USDA farm-fresh vegetables of 1500 boxes.

The dairy products and vegetables can be picked up at the Cumberland County Elementary School, 150 Glasgow Road, Burkesville, KY. The distribution will begin at 9:00 AM CDT on Thursday, September 10, and continue as long as supply lasts.

post_text:
Cumberland County Elementary has been awarded a Fresh Fruit and Vegetable Program (FFVP) USDA grant. The grant is administered by USDA and the Division of School and Community Nutrition, KDE, and coordinated by Cumberland County Board of Education Child Nutrition Services.

A fresh fruit or vegetable snack will be provided for all students at least three days each week.

The Goal of the FFVP is to:
• Create healthier school environments by providing healthier food choices
• Expand the variety of fruits and vegetables children experience
• Increase children’s fruit and vegetable consumption
• Make a difference in children’s diets to impact their present and future health
Snacks will be eaten in your child’s classroom or outside in the afternoons at snack break. Children will be encouraged to try the fruit or vegetable snack each day, but they may opt to not participate if they do not like or cannot eat the fruit or vegetable that day.

post_text: When a student or staff member of Cumberland County Schools presents symptoms that could be COVID related, decisions will be based on this decision tree below. The decision tree takes into account what to do when someone presents symptoms, when someone tests positive, when someone has a household member who tests positive, or when someone has close contact to a positive case. Cumberland County Schools will work closely with the Lake Cumberland Health Department to make decisions by considering the circumstances of each case, and notification will be provided to those who are impacted.

The Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) program provides a benefits card families can use to buy food to replace free school breakfast and lunch while schools are closed. Program enrollment is automatic for children already receiving SNAP (formerly known as food stamps), TANF, Kinship Care, and Medicaid.

Households with children not enrolled in these assistance programs must apply for P-EBT benefits at benefind.ky.gov . Applications will be taken from June 1, 2020 through August 31, 2020.

Cumberland County Schools had originally planned on beginning in-person and online classes on August 13. However, the district then received notice from the KY Department of Education and Governor’s office that stated in-person classes should not begin before August 14 due to increased spread of Covid-19.

Therefore, the decision was made to keep the original start date of August 13 and begin the Virtual Instruction Program (VIP) for all students.

The goal of the school district is to provide a safe return for students to in-person classes as soon as state and public health officials permit. It is not known at this time when that date may be.

Nonetheless, the district is hopeful that resumption of in-person classes may occur as early as the third week of August or soon thereafter.

VIP will also remain as an option all year.

See the link below for Cumberland County School District’s Roadmap to Reopening Plan.

https://www.cland.k12.ky.us/News/737#sthash.ZSFRXq3B.dpbs

post_text:
Counting everyone in your household, including children, ensures they will be included in the 2020 Census. This is important because census statistics help determine funding for the next 10 years for schools and programs such as special education, teacher training, rural education, Head Start, and nutrition assistance. Your response helps shape the future of our children at school and beyond. Yet young children are among the populations historically undercounted in the census.

So please be sure to count all children in your household, including babies born on or before April 1, even if they were still in the hospital on that day. If we do not count everyone in our communities, especially our young children, our area could lose critical funding for programs including those that support education for the next decade.

https://2020census.gov/

Please see this three-page document for frequently asked questions about the one-time benefit of $313.50 per child in the form of an EBT card.

https://benefind.ky.gov/

To locate student ID number: Visit School Website (www.cland.k12.ky.us). Click on the Parent Portal link at the bottom of the District Website. Log in using your username and password. Once you are able to log into the Parent Portal click on the word Today (Located in the upper left menu bar). If you do not see the word Today click the Waffle at the top left of the screen to preview the menu. Under Today you should see your child's Student ID Number and their birthdate. For multiple children click the profile to the right of the screen which should be the student's picture and a drop-down menu button (little arrow) and change to the other child. Click the Today button again to see the Student ID. Repeat steps for multiple children. If you still have issues with finding the Student ID number email lori.spears@cumberland.kyschools.us.

Four CCMS students have been selected to participate in the Rogers Explorers program this summer. They are Rileigh Cobb, JD Riley, Lance Willen, and Isabella Wright.

The Rogers Explorers program is an intensive three-day, two-night program focused on cultivating skills in leadership, technology, math, science, and community service. It is developed, coordinated, and supervised by The Center for Rural Development in partnership with the University of the Cumberlands, Lindsey Wilson College, Eastern Kentucky University, Morehead State University, Asbury University, University of Pikeville, and The Center’s newest partner, Union College.

Congratulations. #PantherProud

post_text: Congratulations to Caity Patterson who has gained acceptance into the 2020 Governors Scholar Program. GSP is a summer residential program for outstanding high school students in Kentucky. The program’s mission is to enhance Kentucky’s next generation of civic and economic leaders. Entry into this program is highly competitive. Students must complete a rigorous application process and submit an academic profile that includes difficulty of course load, GPA, standardized test scores, volunteer service, jobs held, and letters of recommendation from school and community leaders. Congratulations, Caity! We are proud of you!

post_text: Congratulations to Xander Newell and Paris Newell, the most recent CCHS students to gain acceptance into the GSA program. Governors School for the Arts is a summer program with a faculty of professional artists and educators that guide Kentucky’s finest young artists through 3 weeks of intense arts instruction. In order to apply to the program, applicants must go through multiple rounds of auditions, submit letters of reference, and show a high level of skill in the fine arts. Both Paris and Xander were accepted for their work in Drama and Acting.

Cumberland County School District celebrates guidance counselors during National School Counseling Week, February 3-7, 2020. Our counselors serve students in many capacities, guiding their academic and social development. We appreciate all you do for our learners.

CCES counselor Andrea Parson, CCMS counselor Nathalie Vincent, and CCHS counselor Nathan Britt received a gift of appreciation presented by Director of Pupil Personnel Jason Dodson on behalf of Cumberland County Schools.

post_text:
Cumberland County Schools will be closed February 5, 6, and 7, 2020, due to widespread illness. Students should complete work for SLED Days 1, 2, and 3.

Head Start and Little Panthers Daycare will also be closed.

After-school 21st Century activities are canceled effective today. Thursday and Friday night’s basketball games at CCHS will be rescheduled as well as CCES Super Reader recognition.

Saturday’s Governor’s Cup competition is still scheduled to take place.

The Community Education workshop scheduled for Thursday at 5 p.m. will take place.

The Community Baby Shower scheduled for Thursday has been rescheduled for March 26.

post_text:
Cumberland County Community Education would LOVE your participation in an upcoming workshop to paint a 12-inch Valentine’s Day door decoration for yourself or for someone you love! You will be introduced to a few calligraphy basics with this project.

Location: Mary Ann Keen Learning Center

Date and Time: Thursday, February 6, 5:00-7:00 p.m. (Participants may come as early as 3:30 to be finished in time to attend the ball game that night.)

Fee and Registration: $10 (all materials provided) - Limited to 18 participants. Please register by February 4. Make payment in the form of cash or check (made to Cumberland County Board of Education - CCBOE) at the time of the workshop, in person prior to the workshop at the Mary Ann Keen Learning Center, or mailed to Angela Morrison, 810 North Main Street, Burkesville, KY 42717.

Instructor: Angela Morrison

For further information contact Angela Morrison at 270-864-1262 on Mondays through Wednesdays, 8:00-11:00 a.m., or anytime at angela.morrison@cumberland.kyschools.us

post_text: Congratulations to CCHS archery team members competing in S3DA tournament.
shared_text:
Cumberland County High School Burkesville, Kentucky
January 27 at 3:09 PM ·

#CCHSLearners competed at the S3DA Archery Tournament Saturday 1/25/2020 @ Jackson Co. High School. Top shooters were Cameron Watkins with a score of 150 with 20 X’s, Tobie Bean with a score of 139 with 13 X’s and Trent Gilbert with a score of 139 and 9 X’s. Congratulations to all individuals. S3DA is coached by Tabatha Moons.
